    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Paul of Venice considers a sophism involving time and tense which appears to show that there is a valid inference which is also invalid.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Consider this inference concerning some proposition A: A will signify only that everything true will be false, so A will be false.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Then B is valid because the opposite of its conclusion is incompatible with its premise.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Paul takes A to be equivalent to 'Everything that is or will be true will be false'.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "He proceeds to argue that it is possible that B's premise ('A will signify only that everything true will be false') could be true and its conclusion false, so B is not only valid but also invalid.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "On this account, insolubles imply their own falsity, and that is why, in so falsifying themselves, they are false.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Paul argues first that B is invalid and then that B is valid.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "It follows, he says, that our overall question is true: the same inference B can be both valid and invalid.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Paul's response to the temporal insoluble is to accept that B is valid, and to deny that there is any scenario in which its premise is true and conclusion false, as was claimed.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "In his Logica Magna, however, Paul rejects Heytesbury's solution, and passes over the modified version in silence.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Paul adopts and adapts Swyneshed's solution and applies it at length to a range of insolubles.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Insolubles are self-falsifying propositions.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
